You are to design and implement two interacting C++ classes, Game and Scoreboard that together simulate a simplified version of the NCAA basketball scoreboarding system.

Requirements:
Unless otherwise specified, initialize all numeric variables with 0, string variables with "Unknown", enum types with their first element, and pointer variables with a null pointer.
Any member function that does not modify member variables must be declared const.
Define an enum class named Conference for the list of conferences for NCAA Division I sports, with values "ACC", "BIGTEN", "BIG12", "BIGEAST", "IVY", and "SEC".
Define an enum class named State for the list of possible game states, with values "PREGAME", "FIRST_HALF", "HALF_TIME", "SECOND_HALF", "HOME_WINNING", "AWAY_WINNING", and "TIE_GAME". 
Define a struct named Team with the following attributes: 
name, a string, representing the name of the team;
conf, a Conference variable specifying the conference the team is associated with.
Define a class named Game
with the following private data members:
m_home_team: a Team variable specifying the home team.
m_away_team: a Team variable specifying the away team.
m_home_score: an integer variable storing the score for the home team.
m_away_score: an integer variable storing the score for the away team.
m_time_remaining: an integer variable storing the remaining time for the game in seconds. An NCAA basketball game has 40 minutes of playing time, or 2400 seconds. The value of this variable ranges from 0 to 2400, and its default initial value should be 2400. 
and public member functions
Default Constructor that takes no parameter and configure the game with default teams and default values for other member variables.
Parameterized Constructor takes a const reference to Team variable home_team, a const references to Team variable away_team. It sets the other member variables to their default values. If the two teams are the same (they have the same name), the function throws an exception. 
throw std::runtime_error("Invalid game setting");
You may use the <stdexcept> library for the std::runtime_error() function.
Parameterized Constructor takes a const reference to Team variable home_team, a const references to Team variable away_team, and integer variables home_score, away_score, and time_remaining.  If the two teams are the same (they have the same name), or any of the scores are negative, or the remaining time is out of range,  or if it is at the pregame state (remaining time =2400) but the scores are not both zero, the function throws an exception:
throw std::runtime_error("Invalid game setting");
You may use the <stdexcept> library for the std::runtime_error() function.
play function has no return value. It takes three integer inputs: home_added_score, away_added_score, and time_passed. The last int specifies the duration of the passed playing time which should be subtracted from m_time_remaining, and the first two give the added score to the home and away teams respectively.  If any of the added scores are negative, or the passed time is out of range (negative, or larger than m_time_remaining),  the function throws an exception:
throw std::runtime_error("Invalid game play");
You may use the <stdexcept> library for the std::runtime_error() function.
getHomeTeam function returns a const reference to the home team. 
getAwayTeam function returns a const reference to the away team. 
getHomeScore function returns the score of the home team. 
getAwayScore function returns the score of the away team. 
getGameState function returns a variable of State, which is set as follows:
If the remaining time is 2400, the game has not started yet, and the function returns the PREGAME state.
If the remaining time is less than 2400 but larger than 1200, the game is in the FIRST_HALF state.
If the remaining time is 1200, the game is in the HALF_TIME state.
If the remaining time is less than 1200 but larger than 0, the game is in the SECOND_HALF.
If the remaining time is 0, depending on the scores of the home and away teams, the game is in one of the three states: HOME_WINNING, AWAY_WINNING, and TIE_GAME.  
Define a class named Scoreboard
with the following private data members:
m_date: an std::string variable storing the date of the scoreboard.
m_game_list: a pointer variable pointing to a dynamic array of games.
m_num_games: an integer variable storing the number of games in the list. 
and public member functions
Default Constructor sets all member variables to their default values.  
Parameterized Constructor takes a const string reference variable date.
Another Constructor takes a const reference to another Scoreboard variable, named scoreboard and initializes data members with those of scoreboard.
Destructor, which deallocates all dynamically allocated memory.
getNumGames function returns the number of games.
addGame function takes a const reference to a Game object game and tries to add it to the list of games.
It checks if any of the two teams (home or away) in game already plays an existing game in m_game_list. If so, it simply returns false. Otherwise, it will add the game to the end of the dynamic C-style array m_game_list, update m_num_games, and returns true.
NOTE: two teams are considered to be the same if they have the same name. 
NOTE: in class Scoreboard, the private member variables m_home_team and m_away_team of class Game are not directly accessible. 
filterByConference function returns an std::vector of Game objects created by the function, which includes all the games that have at least one of the two teams in the conference specified by an input argument conf of type Conference. If there is no game played by a team of that conference, the function returns an empty vector. 
 

